<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Phyllis W. Jordan 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 FROM SOUTH POLE . . .: When the new "Antarctica Live" series beams into 
classrooms and homes today, viewers across the country will see naval officers 
from Ventura County's two bases, Port Hueneme and Point Mugu. . . . The 
four-part public TV series, which focuses on scientific research in the 
"coldest, windiest, iciest" place on Earth, will also introduce a few of the 
Navy men and women supporting the researchers. Local bases send pilots, weather 
forecasters, doctors, lawyers and chaplains to the frozen continent. Local 
channels don't plan to air the series, but teachers and viewers can get tapes 
by calling (800) 626-LIVE. 
</P>
<P>
 . . . TO NORTH POLE: At the other pole, Santa Claus is preparing for an 
onslaught of mail. E-mail, that is. The Internet provider for Ventura County is 
offering an electronic address for dear old St. Nick. . . . Last year, the 
service drew 9,000 to 11,000 letters from around the world. "It was a 
tremendous response," said Timothy Twinball, of the RAIN Network. The firm sent 
out a mass computer response to most children last year and is setting up a 
committee to send more personal replies. To reach Santa, type: 
santa(at)npole.rain.org 
</P>
<P>
 SLEIGH RIDE: There's no snow to dash through. And the two Belgian draft horses 
don't do much dashing, anyway. Still, Party Animals Farm is trying to create an 
authentic Christmas experience (B4). . . . Visitors to the farm near Moorpark 
sing Christmas carols in the back of a wagon and drink cocoa in front of a 
fire. "It's an old-fashioned way to have a good time," founder Krissie Breck 
says. 
</P>
<P>
 GOLDEN DREAMS: At first, Golden Systems Inc. lived up to its name. After one 
year in business, the Simi Valley firm was selling $4.5 million worth of 
computer power-switching devices. Two years later, sales had risen to $29.4 
million (Valley Business, Page 4). . . . But early this month, the gold lost 
its glitter as defects prompted the firm's largest customer to ship back $5 
million in goods. Now the firm is scrambling to fix the equipment and survive 
the setback. 
</P>
</TEXT>
