<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; PEN PALS MEET FOR LANGUAGE, UNDERSTANDING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAIA DAVIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Ventura High School Spanish teacher Aline Grossman instructed her students to 
exchange letters with Spanish-speaking children to help the teen-agers overcome 
Latino stereotypes. 
</P>
<P>
 And her idea seems to have worked. 
</P>
<P>
 When the two groups met for the first time Monday, many seemed more aware of 
their similarities than their differences. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura High sophomore Robert Napolitano gave his pen pal, 10-year-old Jesus 
Silva, a framed baseball card and some chewing gum for Christmas, along with a 
word of caution. 
</P>
<P>
 "Make sure you chew it at home," 15-year-old Robert said. "I don't want your 
teachers to get (upset)." 
</P>
<P>
 Then the older boy shared even more of his hard-earned wisdom. "You'll really 
like high school," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's so much better than fifth grade." 
</P>
<P>
 Robert and Jesus met at a party in Grossman's classroom, one of five 
get-togethers the teacher held throughout the day for her five Spanish classes 
and their young pen pals from Will Rogers School in Ventura. 
</P>
<P>
 The two groups have been writing letters back and forth this fall in a program 
to enhance the high school students' cultural sensitivity and Spanish 
proficiency. 
</P>
<P>
 The children from Will Rogers are in bilingual classes and many are native 
Spanish speakers just learning English. 
</P>
<P>
 Some of the children, who are in second through fifth grades, wrote their 
letters in English. But many others penned their missives in Spanish, taxing 
the knowledge of the high school students. 
</P>
<P>
 As ninth-grader Rachel Cirricione said: "I had to use my dictionary a lot." 
</P>
<P>
 The younger children also benefit from the letters, getting a thrill from 
corresponding with older students, teachers said. 
</P>
<P>
 Some children even have pictures of their pen pals taped to their school 
desks. 
</P>
<P>
 Mary Perez, a fifth-grader with deeply dimpled cheeks, said she liked having 
ninth-grader Sarah Schwan as a pen pal because "usually I only have friends my 
age." 
</P>
<P>
 And 14-year-old Sarah said the enjoyment was mutual. "It's kind of fun to have 
someone look up to you." MAIA DAVIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
