<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE TIMES' 1994 ALL-COUNTY FOOTBALL TEAM; OFFENSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 FIRST-TEAM PROFILES 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Kevin Feterik 
</P>
<P>
 Position: QB 
</P>
<P>
 School: LOS ALAMITOS 
</P>
<P>
 Year: JR. 
</P>
<P>
 In his first season as a starter, Feterik (6-2, 180) completed 68% of his 
passes for 2,911 yards and 27 touchdowns with only six interceptions, all in 9 
1/2 games. Feterik broke a bone in his left hand in the first half of the 
season opener and missed the next three games. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Dahrin Footman 
</P>
<P>
 Position: RB 
</P>
<P>
 School: ESPERANZA 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. 
</P>
<P>
 Esperanza's one-back offense maximized the number of times Footman (5-8, 185) 
would get the ball. He rushed for 1,852 yards, averaging 7.5 yards per carry, 
and scored 24 touchdowns. Fresno State and Nevada Las Vegas are among the teams 
recruiting him. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Brendan McGraw 
</P>
<P>
 Position: RB 
</P>
<P>
 School: LAGUNA HILLS 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. 
</P>
<P>
 McGraw (6-1, 186) finished second all-time in single-season rushing (2,511 
yards) and first in touchdowns (45) in county, despite skipping six halves--the 
equivalent of three games--because Hawks were so far ahead. California and San 
Diego State are recruiting. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Kris Farris 
</P>
<P>
 Position: OL 
</P>
<P>
 School: SANTA MARGARITA  
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. 
</P>
<P>
 Farris (6-8, 275) has the size scouts drool over. He is an excellent backside 
pass protector and improved his run-blocking this season. He has quick feet, is 
athletic for a big man, and is rarely beaten by opposing defenses. UCLA, USC 
and Stanford are recruiting him. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Jason Grain 
</P>
<P>
 Position: OL 
</P>
<P>
 School: SONORA 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. 
</P>
<P>
 A two-time letterman and All-Freeway League selection, Grain (6-5, 270) can 
count Arizona State, Oregon, Oregon State, UCLA and USC among teams recruiting 
him. Solid as both a run- and pass-blocker. Was Sonora's offensive lineman of 
the year. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Jeff Hagstrom 
</P>
<P>
 Position: OL 
</P>
<P>
 School: IRVINE 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. 
</P>
<P>
 Hagstrom (6-1, 265) is athletic with good quickness, and Irvine Coach Terry 
Henigan says Hagstrom is the strongest football player ever at Irvine. A 
center, the Vaqueros left him to block one-on-one; an excellent run-blocker, he 
was even better against the pass rush. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Matt Motherway 
</P>
<P>
 Position: OL 
</P>
<P>
 School: MATER DEI 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. One of the top linemen prospects in the county. Being recruited by 
USC, UCLA, Colorado and Stanford, among others. A solid run-blocker with quick 
feet. A two-time All-South Coast League selection and three-year letterman. 
Also plays defensive tackle. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Brett Samperi 
</P>
<P>
 Position: OL 
</P>
<P>
 School: SAN CLEMENTE 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. Could be the best lineman in San Clemente history. USC, California, 
Arizona State and Oregon are among the teams recruiting him. Has good speed to 
go with his size (6-5, 270). Could walk in and play at most colleges. A 
two-time All-South Coast League selection. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Brad Melsby 
</P>
<P>
 Position: WR 
</P>
<P>
 School: LOS ALAMITOS 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. 
</P>
<P>
 The Griffins were 39-1-1 during his three-year career. Melsby (6-1, 183) 
finished as Orange County's leader in career receptions (185), yardage (2,979), 
and touchdown receptions (35). UCLA, Stanford, Arizona State and Minnesota are 
among the schools recruiting him. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Rod Perry 
</P>
<P>
 Position: WR 
</P>
<P>
 School: MATER DEI 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SO. 
</P>
<P>
 A fast and dangerous receiver, he had 59 receptions for 1,191 yards--the 
sixth-most in county history. Has scored 16 touchdowns. Scored two touchdowns 
in varsity debut, one on a reverse. Also a talented defensive back, as was his 
father, former Ram Rod Perry Sr. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Brian Forth 
</P>
<P>
 Position: TE 
</P>
<P>
 School: ESPERANZA 
</P>
<P>
 Year: JR. Forth (6-1, 180) has soft hands and was fearless over the middle. He 
was versatile; the Aztecs also used him as an outside receiver and occasionally 
as a wing back to carry the ball. He led the team with 59 receptions for 995 
yards and nine touchdowns. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Student: Patrick Shinnefield 
</P>
<P>
 Position: K  
</P>
<P>
 School: MATER DEI 
</P>
<P>
 Year: SR. 
</P>
<P>
 Had 12 field goals, tops in Orange County and 11th most in county history. Had 
54 conversions. Scored 90 points, most by a kicker since The Times began 
keeping statistics. Has great accuracy and range. His longest field goal was 50 
yards, and he also kicked a 48-yarder. THE SECOND TEAM 
</P>
